McDonald's to open first restaurant in Vietnam
LONDON (MarketWatch) -- McDonald's Corp. MCD, -1.04% will open its first outlet in Vietnam early next year, the burger chain said Tuesday. The restaurant will be in Ho Chi Minh City, and will be operated by Henry Nguyen, a Vietnamese businessman and the son-in-law of Vietnam's Prime Minister Nguyen Tan Dung. McDonald's joins Subway and Starbucks SBUX, -0.03% in setting up operations in the communist country, the 38th Asian nation to welcome the burger business. According to a report in the Financial Times, McDonald's considered entering the Vietnamese market more than 10 years ago, but stumbled on questions of beef supply and reliable supply chain infrastructure.